20] What all collections you used in your project ?

    List Interface : ArrayList | LinkedList

    Set Interface : HashSet | LinkedHashSet | TreeSet

    Map Interface : HashMap | LinkedHashMap | TreeMap



📌 List Interface:

    ⚙ ArrayList: Ordered, allows duplicates (Think: Regular list with indexes)
      - List<Employee> employeeList = new ArrayList<>();

    ⚙ LinkedList: Ordered, allows duplicates (Think: Linked list with nodes, good for frequent insertions/removals)
      - List<Employee> employeeList = new LinkedList<>();

📌 Set Interface:

    ⚙ HashSet: Unordered, doesn't allow duplicates (Think: Unique items in a bag)
      - Set<Employee> uniqueEmployees = new HashSet<>();

    ⚙ LinkedHashSet: Ordered, doesn't allow duplicates (Think: Unique items in a linked list)
      - Set<Employee> uniqueOrderedEmployees = new LinkedHashSet<>();

    ⚙ TreeSet: Ordered, doesn't allow duplicates (Think: Unique items sorted in ascending order)
      - Set<Employee> sortedEmployees = new TreeSet<>();


📌 Map Interface:

    ⚙ HashMap: Unordered, key-value pairs (Think: Dictionary with no specific order for keys)
      - Map<Integer, Employee> employeeMap = new HashMap<>();

    ⚙ LinkedHashMap: Ordered, key-value pairs (Think: Dictionary preserving insertion order)
      - Map<Integer, Employee> employeeMapOrdered = new LinkedHashMap<>();

    ⚙ TreeMap: Ordered, key-value pairs (Think: Dictionary with keys sorted in ascending order)
      - Map<Integer, Employee> employeeMapSorted = new TreeMap<>();


21] What is the difference between list and set ?

    -Order:

    List: Maintains order of elements as they were added.
    Set: Unordered collection, elements may appear in any order.

    -Duplicates:

    List: Allows duplicate elements (can have the same element multiple times).
    Set: Doesn't allow duplicate elements (each element is unique).

